f   Challen   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Challen","meanings":["1  Norman, English: locative name from Chalon-sur-Saône or Châlons-sur-Marne in France.","2  English: nickname possibly from Middle English  <i>chalon</i> ‘blanket’;  see  Challinor  ."]},{"name":"Challens","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Challans  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":67,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":112,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Challons was born in 1270, in England. He married Blance de Waterton. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1270–":"1270–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1270–":"1270–Kuollut","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1298–Female":"1298–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1270–":"1270–Décédé","1275–Female":"1275–Décédée","1298–Female":"1298–Décédée","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"Angleterre","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert de Challons est né en 1270, à Angleterre. Il a épousé Blance de Waterton. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1270–":"1270–Verstorben","1275–Female":"1275–Verstorben","1298–Female":"1298–Verstorben","1270–Male":"1270–Ve